## API Integration Guide

### Authentication Setup
To successfully interact with our API, developers must authenticate every request using a valid API key. We utilize standard Bearer token authentication for all endpoints. Include your secret API key within the `Authorization` header of all HTTP requests. Please ensure you keep your API key secure and never expose it in publicly accessible client-side code, as this directly compromises your account security.

```javascript
// Setup authentication headers
const apiHeaders = {
  'Authorization': 'Bearer YOUR_SECRET_API_KEY',
  'Content-Type': 'application/json'
};
```

### Fetching Data with Pagination
When retrieving large collections of resources, the API returns paginated responses to ensure fast and optimal performance. Our platform relies on cursor-based pagination. You must append the `limit` and `cursor` parameters to your GET request URL. The `limit` dictates the maximum objects returned per page (default 20, maximum 100), while the `cursor` parameter accepts a string provided in the previous response's `next_cursor` field.

```javascript
// Sample GET request fetching paginated user records
async function fetchUsers(cursor = '') {
  const url = `https://api.example.com/v1/users?limit=50&cursor=${cursor}`;
  const response = await fetch(url, { headers: apiHeaders });
  return await response.json();
}
```

### Handling Rate Limit Errors
To prevent platform abuse and ensure maximum stability for all users, the API enforces strict rate limiting. If you exceed the allowed threshold of 100 requests per minute, the API automatically rejects subsequent requests and returns an HTTP `429 Too Many Requests` error.

When encountering this specific rate limit error, you must carefully inspect the `Retry-After` header included in the HTTP response. This header indicates the exact number of seconds your application must wait before attempting another request. Implementing an automated retry mechanism with a sleep function is highly recommended to gracefully handle these temporary rate limits.

```javascript
// Handling a 429 rate limit response gracefully
async function makeApiCall(url) {
  const response = await fetch(url, { headers: apiHeaders });

  if (response.status === 429) {
    const retryAfter = response.headers.get('Retry-After') || 5;
    console.warn(`Rate limited! Retrying in ${retryAfter} seconds.`);

    // Pause execution for the required duration
    await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, retryAfter * 1000));
    return makeApiCall(url);
  }

  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error(`API error: ${response.status}`);
  }

  return response.json();
}
```
